  "dateModified": "2026-03-06",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Long-form copy is persuasive writing that extends over hundreds or thousands of words — sales letters, long landing pages, detailed product pages, and fundraising appeals. It exists because some buying decisions require more persuasion than a headline and a call to action can provide.\nThe length is not arbitrary. Eugene Schwartz argued that copy length should match the reader\u0026rsquo;s awareness level [@schwartz1966]. A reader who already knows the product and is ready to buy needs short copy — a reminder and an offer. A reader who doesn\u0026rsquo;t know the product exists, or doesn\u0026rsquo;t yet recognize the problem it solves, needs long copy — enough to move them through awareness, understanding, differentiation, and decision.\n",
  "name": "Long-Form Copy",
